<!-- doc/src/sgml/custom-stats.sgml -->

<chapter id="custom-stats">
 <title>Custom Cumulative Statistics</title>

 <indexterm zone="custom-stats">
  <primary>custom cumulative statistics</primary>
 </indexterm>

 <indexterm zone="custom-stats">
  <primary>statistics</primary>
  <secondary>extending the cumulative statistics system</secondary>
 </indexterm>

 <para>
  <productname>Apache Cloudberry</productname> exposes a registration entry
  point that lets extensions add their own kinds to the cumulative
  statistics system on top of the built-in kinds (database, relation,
  function, replication-slot, subscription, archiver, bgwriter,
  checkpointer, IO, SLRU, WAL, resource queue). A custom kind owns
  shared-memory hash entries identified by the same <type>(kind, dboid,
  objid)</type> key the built-in kinds use, participates in
  <function>pg_stat_have_stats</function> and
  <function>pg_stat_reset_*</function> automatically, and is read with
  the same <function>pgstat_fetch_entry</function> /
  <function>pgstat_get_entry_ref_locked</function> primitives as core.
 </para>

 <para>
  The API is a backport of <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> 18's
  <quote>Make stats reporting extensible</quote> change (commit
  <literal>f98dbdeb51</literal>); modules written against upstream PG 18+
  can be ported to <productname>Apache Cloudberry</productname> with no
  source changes by including the <filename>utils/pgstat_kind.h</filename>
  compatibility header.
 </para>

 <sect1 id="custom-stats-overview">
  <title>Overview</title>

  <para>
   Custom kinds are designed for the same workload the built-in cumulative
   statistics serve: low-volume, write-mostly counters that need to be
   visible cluster-wide and survive across sessions but not across
   crashes.
  </para>

  <para>
   For workloads that need every-call/every-row instrumentation
   (per-statement timing, per-row sampling) the cumulative statistics
   system is the wrong layer; use a hook + ring buffer or
   <filename>pg_stat_statements</filename>-style hashtable instead.
  </para>
 </sect1>

 <sect1 id="custom-stats-limitations">
  <title>Limitations and Constraints</title>

  <itemizedlist>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <emphasis>Registration is process-local.</emphasis> Each backend
     populates its own table of custom kinds during startup. To stay
     consistent across the cluster, the module must be loaded via
     <xref linkend="guc-shared-preload-libraries"/>; calls to
     <function>pgstat_register_kind</function> outside
     <symbol>process_shared_preload_libraries_in_progress</symbol>
     raise an error.
    </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <emphasis>Reserved ID range.</emphasis> Custom kinds use IDs
     <literal>PGSTAT_KIND_CUSTOM_MIN .. PGSTAT_KIND_CUSTOM_MAX</literal>
     (currently 24..31, eight slots). Built-in kinds occupy
     <literal>PGSTAT_KIND_BUILTIN_MIN .. PGSTAT_KIND_BUILTIN_MAX</literal>
     and are off-limits; the gap between the ranges is reserved for
     future built-in additions and must not be used by extensions.
    </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <emphasis>No persistence across postmaster restarts.</emphasis>
     The on-disk stats file format only persists built-in kinds in this
     port. Custom-kind entries live in the shared-memory hash for the
     lifetime of the postmaster and start empty after every restart.
     Extensions that need durable counters must serialize them
     themselves (file in <varname>$PGDATA/pg_stat/</varname> with an
     atomic-rename pattern is the conventional choice).
    </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <emphasis>One <type>PgStat_KindInfo</type> per kind, valid for the
     life of the process.</emphasis>
     <function>pgstat_register_kind</function> stores a pointer to the
     supplied descriptor; the storage must remain valid until process
     exit. The usual pattern is a <literal>static const</literal> in the
     module's source file.
    </para>
   </listitem>
  </itemizedlist>
 </sect1>

 <sect1 id="custom-stats-defining-kind">
  <title>Defining a Custom Kind</title>

  <para>
   A custom kind is described by <type>PgStat_KindInfo</type> declared in
   <filename>utils/pgstat_internal.h</filename>. The structure carries
   sizing information, persistence flags, and pointers to optional
   callbacks. The fields most modules need are:
  </para>

  <variablelist>
   <varlistentry>
    <term><structfield>name</structfield> <type>(const char *)</type></term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Short identifier &mdash; appears in
     <function>pg_stat_have_stats('<replaceable>name</replaceable>',
     ...)</function> and in error messages. Must be non-empty and
     unique across all registered kinds.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term><structfield>fixed_amount</structfield> <type>(bool)</type></term>
    <listitem>
     <para><literal>false</literal> for kinds with one entry per
     object (relation, database, custom OID); <literal>true</literal>
     for cluster-wide singletons (archiver, WAL).
     <literal>fixed_amount = true</literal> requires
     <structfield>snapshot_cb</structfield> and
     <structfield>reset_all_cb</structfield>.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term><structfield>accessed_across_databases</structfield> <type>(bool)</type></term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Set to <literal>true</literal> when entries should be
     visible from any database (rather than only from the database
     whose OID matches <literal>key.dboid</literal>). Database-level
     aggregates and cluster-wide objects use this.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term>
     <structfield>shared_size</structfield>,
     <structfield>shared_data_off</structfield>,
     <structfield>shared_data_len</structfield>
     <type>(uint32)</type>
    </term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Total size of one shared-memory entry (header +
     payload), the offset of the payload within that entry, and the
     payload size. The header is always
     <type>PgStatShared_Common</type>; embed it as the first field of
     your shared struct so the offsets line up.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term><structfield>pending_size</structfield> <type>(uint32)</type></term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Size of the optional per-backend pending buffer, or 0 if
     the kind writes shared memory directly.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term><structfield>flush_pending_cb</structfield> <type>(callback)</type></term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Required when <structfield>pending_size</structfield>
     &gt; 0. Invoked from
     <function>pgstat_report_stat()</function> to merge the
     backend-local pending entry into the shared entry.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term>
     <structfield>delete_pending_cb</structfield>,
     <structfield>reset_timestamp_cb</structfield>,
     <structfield>to_serialized_name</structfield>,
     <structfield>from_serialized_name</structfield>,
     <structfield>reset_all_cb</structfield>,
     <structfield>snapshot_cb</structfield>
     <type>(callbacks)</type>
    </term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Optional hooks for advanced lifecycle events (drop
     pending, reset timestamp, name-keyed identification on disk,
     fixed-kind reset/snapshot). Most variable-numbered kinds need
     none of these.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term>
     <structfield>write_to_file</structfield>,
     <structfield>track_entry_count</structfield>
     <type>(bool : 1)</type>
    </term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Forward-compatibility flags reserved for future use. They
     are accepted by the registration call so modules written against
     <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> 18+ continue to compile;
     in the current port they are informational. Persistence is not
     implemented for custom kinds (see
     <xref linkend="custom-stats-limitations"/>) and
     <function>pgstat_get_entry_count</function> walks the shared
     hash regardless.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
  </variablelist>
 </sect1>

 <sect1 id="custom-stats-registering">
  <title>Registering a Kind</title>

  <para>
   The module exposes a <type>PgStat_KindInfo</type> object and registers
   it from <function>_PG_init</function>:
  </para>

<programlisting>
#include "utils/pgstat_kind.h"
#include "utils/pgstat_internal.h"

typedef struct PgStatShared_MyEntry
{
    PgStatShared_Common header;
    MyCounters          stats;
}           PgStatShared_MyEntry;

static const PgStat_KindInfo my_kind_info = {
    .name              = "my_module",
    .fixed_amount      = false,
    .shared_size       = sizeof(PgStatShared_MyEntry),
    .shared_data_off   = offsetof(PgStatShared_MyEntry, stats),
    .shared_data_len   = sizeof(MyCounters),
    .pending_size      = 0,
    .flush_pending_cb  = NULL,
};

#define PGSTAT_KIND_MY_MODULE  (PGSTAT_KIND_CUSTOM_MIN + 0)

void
_PG_init(void)
{
    /* must be loaded via shared_preload_libraries */
    pgstat_register_kind(PGSTAT_KIND_MY_MODULE, &amp;my_kind_info);
}
</programlisting>

  <para>
   <function>pgstat_register_kind</function> validates that the chosen
   ID is in the custom range, that the slot is empty, that the
   <structfield>name</structfield> is non-empty, and that the call
   happens during shared-library preload. Successful registrations are
   logged at <literal>LOG</literal> level so operators can confirm what
   modules have claimed which slots.
  </para>

  <para>
   Picking an ID is the responsibility of the module author. The
   eight-slot range is small, so well-known modules should pick an
   offset and document it in their README; cluster operators that
   combine modules can resolve collisions by recompiling one of them
   with a different offset.
  </para>
 </sect1>

 <sect1 id="custom-stats-using">
  <title>Reading and Writing Entries</title>

  <para>
   Once a kind is registered, entries are accessed exactly like
   built-in kinds. Writing is done under the per-entry LWLock provided
   by the cumulative statistics system:
  </para>

<programlisting>
PgStat_EntryRef       *entry_ref;
PgStatShared_MyEntry  *shentry;

entry_ref = pgstat_get_entry_ref_locked(PGSTAT_KIND_MY_MODULE,
                                        MyDatabaseId, my_objid,
                                        false /* nowait */);

shentry = (PgStatShared_MyEntry *) entry_ref-&gt;shared_stats;
shentry-&gt;stats.calls++;
shentry-&gt;stats.total_time += elapsed_ms;

pgstat_unlock_entry(entry_ref);
</programlisting>

  <para>
   Reading uses the same fetch path as core, including
   <function>pgstat_fetch_entry</function> for snapshot-aware lookups
   from SQL-callable functions:
  </para>

<programlisting>
MyCounters *snap;

snap = (MyCounters *)
    pgstat_fetch_entry(PGSTAT_KIND_MY_MODULE,
                       MyDatabaseId, my_objid);
if (snap == NULL)
    PG_RETURN_NULL();
</programlisting>

  <para>
   Resetting works through the standard primitives. For a single entry:
  </para>

<programlisting>
pgstat_reset_entry(PGSTAT_KIND_MY_MODULE, dboid, objid, GetCurrentTimestamp());
</programlisting>

  <para>
   For all entries of the kind:
  </para>

<programlisting>
pgstat_reset_of_kind(PGSTAT_KIND_MY_MODULE);
</programlisting>

  <para>
   To find out how many entries of the kind currently exist in shared
   memory (useful for capacity tracking and admin views):
  </para>

<programlisting>
int64 n = pgstat_get_entry_count(PGSTAT_KIND_MY_MODULE);
</programlisting>
 </sect1>

 <sect1 id="custom-stats-sql">
  <title>SQL Surface</title>

  <para>
   <function>pg_stat_have_stats(<replaceable>kind_name</replaceable>,
   <replaceable>dboid</replaceable>,
   <replaceable>objid</replaceable>)</function> resolves
   <replaceable>kind_name</replaceable> against the union of built-in
   and registered custom names. A custom kind's SQL identity is its
   <structfield>name</structfield> field exactly as registered:
  </para>

<programlisting>
SELECT pg_stat_have_stats('my_module', current_database()::oid, '...'::oid);
</programlisting>

  <para>
   <function>pg_stat_reset</function> with the kind name argument
   targets a custom kind in the same way. Modules typically also
   ship dedicated views and reset functions wrapping
   <function>pgstat_fetch_entry</function> for per-object queries
   (the schema, view names, and column shape are entirely up to the
   module).
  </para>
 </sect1>

 <sect1 id="custom-stats-cookbook">
  <title>Implementation Notes</title>

  <itemizedlist>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <emphasis>Concurrency.</emphasis> Each shared entry has its own
     LWLock acquired by
     <function>pgstat_get_entry_ref_locked</function>. Hold it as
     briefly as possible &mdash; treat the entry like any other shared
     memory critical section. For high-frequency updates use the
     per-backend pending-buffer pattern (set
     <structfield>pending_size</structfield> and provide
     <structfield>flush_pending_cb</structfield>) so the lock is taken
     once at flush time rather than on every increment.
    </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <emphasis>Object identity.</emphasis> The hash key is
     <type>(kind, dboid, objid)</type>. Modules that want
     finer-grained partitioning than a single OID typically encode a
     compound key into <literal>objid</literal>; for example, a
     vacuum-stats module may pack
     <literal>(reloid &lt;&lt; 2) | type_tag</literal> to track table
     and index entries for the same OID separately.
     <literal>dboid = InvalidOid (0)</literal> is the conventional
     choice for cluster-wide entries that
     <structfield>accessed_across_databases</structfield> exposes
     everywhere.
    </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <emphasis>Drop semantics.</emphasis> The cumulative statistics
     system does not know the lifecycle of objects identified by
     <literal>objid</literal>; if entries should disappear when an
     object is dropped, register an
     <function>object_access_hook</function> with
     <literal>OAT_DROP</literal> and call
     <function>pgstat_reset_entry</function> from there.
    </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <emphasis>Memory accounting.</emphasis> Each entry consumes
     <structfield>shared_size</structfield> bytes plus DSA hash
     overhead. The module can expose
     <function>pgstat_get_entry_count(kind) *
     sizeof(<replaceable>shared_struct</replaceable>)</function> as a
     SQL-callable estimate of its footprint; cluster operators use
     this for capacity planning.
    </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <emphasis>Forward compatibility.</emphasis> Modules that target
     <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> 18+ as well should include
     <filename>utils/pgstat_kind.h</filename> rather than reaching
     into <filename>utils/pgstat_internal.h</filename> directly. The
     compatibility shim re-exports the registration API, and the
     <structfield>write_to_file</structfield> /
     <structfield>track_entry_count</structfield> flags accept the
     same values they take upstream.
    </para>
   </listitem>
  </itemizedlist>
 </sect1>

 <sect1 id="custom-stats-reference">
  <title>Function Reference</title>

  <variablelist>
   <varlistentry>
    <term>
     <function>void pgstat_register_kind(PgStat_Kind kind, const PgStat_KindInfo *kind_info)</function>
    </term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Register <parameter>kind_info</parameter> as the descriptor for
      cumulative statistics kind <parameter>kind</parameter>. The
      <parameter>kind</parameter> must be in the
      <literal>PGSTAT_KIND_CUSTOM_MIN .. PGSTAT_KIND_CUSTOM_MAX</literal>
      range and not already registered. The
      <parameter>kind_info</parameter> pointer must remain valid for the
      lifetime of the process. Must be called during
      <symbol>process_shared_preload_libraries_in_progress</symbol>;
      otherwise raises <literal>ERROR</literal>.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term>
     <function>int64 pgstat_get_entry_count(PgStat_Kind kind)</function>
    </term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Return the number of entries in shared memory whose key matches
      <parameter>kind</parameter>. Walks the cumulative statistics
      shared hash holding a shared exclusive lock; treat as O(N) over
      total entries and avoid calling on hot paths.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
  </variablelist>

  <para>
   The remaining primitives (<function>pgstat_get_entry_ref_locked</function>,
   <function>pgstat_unlock_entry</function>,
   <function>pgstat_fetch_entry</function>,
   <function>pgstat_reset_entry</function>,
   <function>pgstat_reset_of_kind</function>,
   <function>pgstat_have_entry</function>) are unchanged from the
   built-in cumulative statistics system; refer to their declarations
   in <filename>utils/pgstat_internal.h</filename> and
   <filename>pgstat.h</filename>.
  </para>
 </sect1>

</chapter>
